(8, 5, NULL, 1, 1, 'Explore Laos', 'explore-laos', '', '/mix/view/admin/Themes/kcfinder/upload/images/tour/love-travel-27-780.jpg', '500', '0', '0', '0', '0', '0', '11 Days 10 Nights', 'Houay Xay', 'Luang Prabang', '', 'Car', 4, '<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Your adventure into the heart and soul of Laos will begin at the border crossing of&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Houay Xay</strong>. Here you will be met by your local Mixtourist guide who will escort you to your boat for your overnight cruise to<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Luang Prabang.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	En route you&rsquo;ll make a stop to visit an authentic hill tribe settlement where you can enjoy observing the genuine way of existence and see how the locals utilize the&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Mekong River&nbsp;</strong>as a source of life. Along the way you&rsquo;ll enjoy a delicious buffet lunch onboard your boat and in the afternoon you&rsquo;ll come to rest at<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Pakbeng.</strong></p>\r\n', '<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Your adventure into the heart and soul of Laos will begin at the border crossing of&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Houay Xay</strong>. Here you will be met by your local Mixtourist guide who will escort you to your boat for your overnight cruise to<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Luang Prabang.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	En route you&rsquo;ll make a stop to visit an authentic hill tribe settlement where you can enjoy observing the genuine way of existence and see how the locals utilize the&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Mekong River&nbsp;</strong>as a source of life. Along the way you&rsquo;ll enjoy a delicious buffet lunch onboard your boat and in the afternoon you&rsquo;ll come to rest at<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Pakbeng.</strong></p>\r\n', '<h2 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; font-family: Arial; background-image: none; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-size: 17px !important;">\r\n	<span style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);"><strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: small;">Day 1: HOUAY XAY - PAKBENG (L, D)&nbsp;</strong></span></h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Your adventure into the heart and soul of Laos will begin at the border crossing of&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Houay Xay</strong>. Here you will be met by your local Mixtourist guide who will escort you to your boat for your overnight cruise to<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Luang Prabang.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	En route you&rsquo;ll make a stop to visit an authentic hill tribe settlement where you can enjoy observing the genuine way of existence and see how the locals utilize the&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Mekong River&nbsp;</strong>as a source of life. Along the way you&rsquo;ll enjoy a delicious buffet lunch onboard your boat and in the afternoon you&rsquo;ll come to rest at<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Pakbeng.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Situated halfway between Houay Xay and Luang Prabang, the quaint rural hillside town is most certainly relaxed and is home to a good number of tasty local restaurants. You&rsquo;ll arrive in Pakbeng just in time to see the sunset over the Mekong. Overnight in Pakbeng</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; font-family: Arial; background-image: none; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify; font-size: 17px !important;">\r\n	<span style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: small; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Day 2: PAKBENG - PAK OU - LUANG PRABANG&nbsp; ( B, L)</span></h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Early risers can pay a visit to the morning market to see local residents and hill tribes all converge to buy, sell and exchange their wares. We&rsquo;ll get back on the boat at 8.30am and cruise down the Mekong to see how traditional rice alcohol or&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">&lsquo;Lao Lao&rsquo;</strong>&nbsp;is made at the village of&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Ban Baw.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Take lunch on board as we carry on cruising to the&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Pak Ou Caves</strong>, known locally as&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">&lsquo;Tam Ting</strong>&rsquo;. These two caves are carved out of a huge limestone cliff and are filled with thousands of gold lacquered Buddha statues, some only a few centimeters in height and some as tall as a person. These caves are an important<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Buddhist pilgrimage</strong>&nbsp;site and you will see many people visit them in&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Pii Mai, Lao New Year</strong>.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	After visiting the Pak Ou Caves you will be met by your private driver and our guide for a transfer to your hotel. Overnight in<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">&nbsp;Luang Prabang</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; font-family: Arial; background-image: none; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify; font-size: 17px !important;">\r\n	<span style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: small; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Day 3: LUANG PRABANG (B)</span></h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Your tour of Luang Prabang will begin at the former&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Royal Palace</strong>&nbsp;which now exists as the&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">National Museum</strong>. Here you can learn about Laos&rsquo; rich history and culture and there are usually special exhibits on display to see. You&rsquo;ll then move on to&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Wat Mai Buddhist temple</strong>, one of the most richly decorated temples of Luang Prabang and&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Wat Sensoukarahm</strong>, which is decorated in a stenciled gold fa&ccedil;ade.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	To round off your morning you will visit&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Wat Xieng Thong</strong>, the most famous temple in Luang Prabang. This temple, also known as&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Temple of the Golden City</strong>, rests on the northern tip of the peninsula close to the Mekong River. The temple was built by&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">King Setthathirat</strong>&nbsp;in 1560 and remains a significant spiritual place in Laos.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	If you wish, in the evening you can attend a personal Baci ceremony. These ceremonies are deeply rooted in the Laos culture and are used to celebrate a special occasion - whether a wedding, an annual festival, or as a welcome.&nbsp; Overnight in Luang Prabang</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; font-family: Arial; background-image: none; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify; font-size: 17px !important;">\r\n	<span style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: small; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Day 4: LUANG PRABANG - KUANG SI WATERFALL - LUANG FRABANG</span></h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial; text-align: justify;">This morning you have the option of getting up early to observe the local monks collecting alms. The rising sun brings with it long lines of orange-robed monks who walk barefoot around the city collecting offerings made by locals and should be seen at least once. You can then return to the hotel and take advantage of being one of the first to reach the breakfast service!</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	After breakfast your guide will pick you up in a private car and whisk you out into the countryside, taking you on an hour-long drive through beautiful landscapes, small villages and rice paddies. You will make a brief stop at one of the villages before coming to rest at the famous&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Kuang Si Waterfalls.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	An elegant three-tier waterfall, the main fall of Kuang Si is approximately 60 meters high and there are several turquoise blue pools in which to bathe or swim. If you&rsquo;re in the mood for some gentle exercise, there&rsquo;s the chance to scale the track up to the top of the falls which provide spectacular views of the surrounding area.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Once you&rsquo;ve had your fill of the natural beauty around the falls you will next have the opportunity to visit the<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Tat Kuang Si Bear Rescue Center</strong>&nbsp;located near the falls. The center is home to around a dozen sun bears that were rescued from the grasps of poachers. The center attempts to rehabilitate the bears and raise awareness of the plight the endangered species face.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	The remainder of your final day in&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Luang Prabang</strong>&nbsp;will be spent at your own leisure, but be sure to ask your guide if you would like any recommendations for delicious local food, or even the best place to grab a refreshing cocktail. Overnight in Luang Prabang</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; font-family: Arial; background-image: none; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify; font-size: 17px !important;">\r\n	<span style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: small; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Day 5: LUANG PRABANG - VANG VIENG(B)</span></h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	After breakfast you&rsquo;ll depart for&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Vang Vieng</strong>, taking a five-hour drive with a stop along the way in Kasi, a rural region famous for its delicious fruit. Your journey will take you down numerous picturesque, winding mountain roads lined with spectacular scenery.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Vang Vieng is a quaint, laid-back town on the banks of the&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Nam Song River</strong>&nbsp;flanked by outstanding limestone karst landscapes which surround the town. Vang Vieng was originally settled in the early 1350s. It was then known as Mouang Song but renamed Vang Vieng during French colonial times in the 19th century.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Your afternoon will be free to spend at your leisure with a driver and expert Mixtourist guide at your disposal. Feel free to ask their advice on one of the many exciting activities available. Perhaps you might like to explore the exquisite cave formations, nearby villages and a local organic farm where you can stop to enjoy a cup of delicious mulberry tea.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	If you&rsquo;re feeling active and adventurous you can take your pick of numerous outdoor activities such as cycling, kayaking, rock climbing, trekking and tubing. These activities are not included in your tour but can be easily arranged. Overnight in Vang Vieng</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; font-family: Arial; background-image: none; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify; font-size: 17px !important;">\r\n	<span style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: small; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Day 6: VANG VIENG - VIENTIANE (B)</span></h3>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	After breakfast you will be transfer by your private driver and Mixtourist guide to&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Vientiane</strong>, stopping after 90 minutes at&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Nam Ngum Lake</strong>, the largest lake in Laos. An artificial lake, Nam Ngum was the first hydroelectric dam built in Laos to produce electricity.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	You are welcome to take your lunch here (not included) or hire a boat for a short tour of the lake (also not included).</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	You&rsquo;ll then continue your drive on to Vientiane, a journey which should take approximately two and a half hours. Upon arrival you will enjoy spending the rest of the day at your leisure, perhaps taking an evening promenade along the banks of the Mekong and stop at the daily night market. Overnight in Vientiane</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; font-family: Arial; background-image: none; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify; font-size: 17px !important;">\r\n	<span style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: small; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Day 7: VIENTIANE (B)</span></h3>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Today go on a guided tour of the Laos capital,&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Vientiane.</strong>&nbsp;Situated on a bend of the Mekong River, Vientiane is one of the smallest capital cities in the world, and many of its treasures can be unearthed simply by putting on one&rsquo;s walking shoes (or sandals!) and exploring the place on foot.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Start near the center of town at&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Wat Sisaket</strong>,&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Vientiane&rsquo;s oldest surviving temple</strong>. The courtyard contains over 300 different Buddha images, either sculpted or cast in the characteristic Lao style. Next is<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Wat Phra Keo</strong>, which displays both Khmer and Lao works of art and now serves as a religious museum.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Next you will visit&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">COPE,</strong>&nbsp;an association that works to help landmine victims from unexploded ordinances left over from the Vietnam War with the USA.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Hit the streets again in the afternoon as we go to Patuxay, situated at the end of&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Lane Xang</strong>, a large, tree-lined avenue. This Arc De Triomphe inspired building also incorporates traditional Lao motifs such as &lsquo;Kinnari&rsquo;, the mythical bird-woman said to represent feminine beauty, grace and accomplishment.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Climb to the top and get fantastic panoramic views of the city. After coming down, it&rsquo;s a short drive to the holiest site in Laos,&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Lao&rsquo;s National Monument:</strong>&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Tat Luang.</strong>&nbsp;Constructed in the 16<sup style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">th</sup>&nbsp;century by King Setthethirat, its sharp angles and beautiful decoration make it an arresting sight as the sun shines on its gold-leaf and towering main spire.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Another holy site is next.&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Wat Simuang</strong>&nbsp;is the most venerated temple in Vientiane, as it is believed to be the guardian of the spirit of the city. Walk around its main<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">, Angkorian-era pillar</strong>&nbsp;three times and make a wish. It is believed that if you do this your wish will be granted. Overnight in Vientiane</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; font-family: Arial; background-image: none; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify; font-size: 17px !important;">\r\n	<span style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: small; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Day 8: VIENTIANE - BAN KONGLOR (B, L)</span></h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	An early rise is recommended this morning as your local Mixtourist guide will meet you at 8am to embark up the journey southbound to&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Ban Kong Lor</strong>&nbsp;along highway 13. After driving for three hours you will make a stop at&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Wat Prabath Phonsane</strong>, also known as Temple of the Footprint of Buddha.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	After the temple you will leave the highway and enter the&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Phou Hin Poun</strong>&nbsp;region, a National Protected Area. The scenery along the two-hour drive becomes even more outstanding as you journey past spectacular limestone karsts, lush forests and rice paddies. A delightful picnic lunch (brought from Vientiane) will be taken at a suitable spot whenever you prefer.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	On arrival in the quaint town of&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Ban Kong Lor</strong>&nbsp;you&rsquo;ll be able to check in and freshen up before heading out to explore the famous Kong Lor Caves. The 7.5km stretch of caves is the longest and most spectacular cave complex in Laos. After donning a life jacket and head torch you&rsquo;ll board a long tail boat and take a cruise along the underground Hin Boun River section.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Inside the caves you will be able to explore the vast formations of stalactites and stalagmites on foot, led by your expert guide. Certain places in the caves reach up to 100m high and 90m wide. The cave is still used by local villagers as a thoroughfare &ndash; it&rsquo;s certainly much quicker taking this route rather than climbing over the mountains the cave cuts through!</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Once you emerge out of the other side you can stop for refreshments at one of the local villages to enjoy the ambience and culture of rural life in Laos. You will later make the return journey by boat, travelling downstream through the cave back to Ban Kong Lor. Overnight in Ban Kong Lor</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; font-family: Arial; background-image: none; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify; font-size: 17px !important;">\r\n	<span style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: small; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Day 9: KONG LOR CAVES - THAKLEK -SAVANNAKHET (B)</span></h3>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Take advantage of the crisp clear morning air and take a walk before breakfast around the surrounding picturesque villages accompanied by your expert local guide. Early mornings are fascinating insights into local life as people prepare for their upcoming day.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	You&rsquo;ll then embark upon your journey to Savannakhet, stopping after four hours at Thakhek, just in time for lunch at your leisure. Thakhek is a quaint, sleepy town with many attractive colonial buildings and makes for a relaxing pit stop before you continue on the 90-minute journey to Savannakhet.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Before entering the town of&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Savannakhe</strong>t you will make a stop at the beautiful 16th Century temple of<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">That Ing Hang</strong>. An impressive central stupa dominates a courtyard which is flanked by statues of Lord Buddha, in a style similar to Wat Sisaket in Vientiane. That Ing Hang is among the most revered temples in Laos and many Buddhists will travel here during December for the annual &lsquo;Boun Phathat&rsquo; ceremony.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	You&rsquo;ll then continue to&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Savannakhet,</strong>&nbsp;a city famous for being the birthplace of the father of the Lao People&rsquo;s Democratic Republic (Lao PDR), Kaysone Phomvihane.Led by your expert Mixtourist guide you&rsquo;ll enjoy a short tour of the architectural highlights including the remarkable&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">St. Teresa Catholic Church</strong>.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	The day is then yours to enjoy as you wish. If you like, you can pay a visit to the fascinating&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Dinosaur Museum</strong>. The museum contains dinosaur remains found by paleontologists nearby which are between 150 &ndash; 250 million years old. Overnight in Savannakhet</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; font-family: Arial; background-image: none; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify; font-size: 17px !important;">\r\n	<span style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: small; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Day 10: SAVANAKHET - SALAVAN - TAD LO - TAD ETU ( B)</span></h3>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	We&rsquo;ll set-off early for today&rsquo;s drive to the&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Bolaven Plateau</strong>. Take a stop at the Tad Lo area to see its three different waterfalls:&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Tad Hang, Tad Lo and Tad Suong</strong>. Continue to the twin waterfalls of&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Tad Yuang and Tad Fane,</strong>&nbsp;which pour down into a gorge in the dense jungle. Both tea and coffee are produced in this region, cultivated between 1000-1300 meters above sea level by the families who inhabit the 250 villages of the area. We&rsquo;ll pay a visit to one of these plantations. Overnight in Tad Etu</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; font-family: Arial; background-image: none; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify; font-size: 17px !important;">\r\n	<span style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: small; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Day 11: TAD ETU - WAT PHOU - KHONG ISLAND (B)</span></h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Drive to the UNESCO World Heritage Site of&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Wat Phou</strong>. This spectacular temple pre-dates Angkor Wat and was built by the rulers of the Khmer empire. The temple is constructed on three levels: the water reservoir, the galleries and the sanctuary itself, it is one of the holiest temples of the Laos people.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	You&rsquo;ll then pass through&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Champasak,</strong>&nbsp;a quaint town where French colonial buildings offer a pronounced contrast to Wat Phou, before continuing south, making a brief stop at the small village of&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Ban Nong Bune</strong>, renowned for its delicate wood carvings.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	On arrival in&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Ban Kiet Ngong</strong>&nbsp;you&rsquo;ll enjoy lunch in a simple local restaurant before taking your 90-minute elephant ride through the forest to Mount Asa. This tour is part of a community-based project designed to help the local villagers.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	During your elephant ride you&rsquo;ll enjoy spectacular views of Xe Pian National Park. The park is a vast region of wetlands and lush green forest that lines the Mekong River with an astounding 29 recorded ecosystems. Here you may be able to spot numerous species of bird such as egrets, sarus crane and hornbill, not to mention other inhabitants including wild elephants and gibbons.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	After your elephant ride through the park, your Mixtourist guide will lead you south to&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Si Phan Don</strong>, the 4000 Islands Region. Here the Mekong River stretches to over 14km wide and flows around, between, over and under an uncountable number of islands, creating waterfalls and rapids.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Once you arrive at the Mekong, you&rsquo;ll take a short boat crossing to your hotel, arriving sometime in the late afternoon. Your evening will then be free to spend at your leisure. Overnight in&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Khong Island</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; font-family: Arial; background-image: none; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify; font-size: 17px !important;">\r\n	<span style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: small; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Day 12: KHONG ISLAND - SIPHANDON - PAKSE (B)</span></h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Our guide will meet you after breakfast and you&rsquo;ll then venture out together to explore the peaceful villages and plantations of&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Don Det and Don Khone</strong>&nbsp;islands.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	On your outward bound boat trip you might even have the unique chance to spot the rare&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Irrawaddy Dolphin</strong>. Sightings aren&rsquo;t guaranteed, but mornings and late afternoons when the water is cooler offer the best opportunity. Once you land upon the island you can opt for either a bike tour or tuk-tuk ride to explore the islands.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	You&rsquo;ll visit the impressive&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Lippi</strong>&nbsp;falls next, which lie to the west of Don Khone, close to the Cambodian border. Known as&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Tad Somphamit</strong>&nbsp;(&lsquo;trap spirit&rsquo;) to locals, islanders believe the falls act as a trap to catch bad spirits.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	These islands played a crucial role during the times of French occupation as they linked Laos and Cambodia and Vietnam&rsquo;s south. A railway and bridge were built across the waterfalls and is a perfect place to soak up the spectacular surrounding views.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	You&rsquo;ll continue your exploration at a lazy, relaxed stride as you adapt to the steady pace of local life, led by your expert local Mixtourist guide before taking lunch at a local restaurant.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	Your day will end will a trip to the spectacular&nbsp;<strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Khone Papheng</strong>&nbsp;waterfalls, where you can take time to appreciate the sensational view as you reflect upon your memorable exploration of majestic Myanmar before moving on to Pakse for your last night.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; font-family: Arial; background-image: none; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify; font-size: 17px !important;">\r\n	<span style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: small; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Day 13: PAKSE&nbsp; ( B)</span></h3>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style="color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial; text-align: justify;">After breakfast your guide will meet you at the hotel for your transfer to either the Thai border or the airport for your departure flight.</span></p>\r\n', '<h2 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-stretch: normal; line-height: normal; font-family: Arial; background-image: none; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: center; font-size: 17px !important;">\r\n	<span style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">PACKAGE PRICE: CONTACT US</span></h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 21px; text-align: justify; color: rgb(60, 59, 59); font-family: Arial;">\r\n	&nb